The House of Representatives yesterday passed for second reading a bill seeking to repeal the Terrorism (prevention) Act, 2011 and enact a new law. The bill, sponsored by Kayode Oladele (APC, Ogun) seeks to come up with terrorism law that would provide measures for prohibition, prevention and combating terrorism activities in Nigeria. Leading the debate on the bill, Oladele said it sought to harmonize the Terrorism Act and control the movement of explosives, arms and ammunition in Nigeria with a view to checking the activities of terrorists. The bill was unanimously passed for second reading when Speaker Yakubu Dogara put it to voice vote.